        s: "When starting as a Consultant at SEFAZ/RS, the State General Accounting and Audit Office (CAGE) did not have a structured PMO. Critical projects were managed ad-hoc, with 3 duplicated initiatives consuming R$ 4.2M without anyone noticing the overlap. With the arrival of the PROFISCO II program (R$ 180M financed by IDB), the requirement for transparency, accountability, and measurable results delivery became mandatory. IDB required detailed monthly reports and quarterly audits - capabilities that simply didn't exist.",
        t: "My responsibility was literally to create CAGE's first institutional PMO from scratch. I identified that no entity had clarity about project RACI, resulting in operational chaos where everyone was responsible for everything, therefore no one was responsible for anything. I was the 'owner' of the mission to transform project management from a reactive and fragmented model to a strategic, integrated, and data-driven model.",
        a: "I identified that hiring consultancy would cost R$ 800k-1.2M and generate a generic framework with low adoption. I opted for a more strategic approach: create internally to maximize customization and team ownership. I spent 3 weeks studying frameworks (PMI, PRINCE2, SAFe) and decided to adapt PMI for better fit with Brazilian public culture and IDB requirements. I personally wrote 3 manuals (147 pages total): Project Management Manual (62 pages), Portfolio Management Manual (48 pages), Risk Management Manual (37 pages). I created all 31 templates in SharePoint: Project Charter, WBS, Schedule, RACI Matrix, Risk Register, Status Dashboard, etc. Impact was immediate: time spent by managers looking for templates reduced from 4h/week to 20min/week (87% improvement), and adherence to new reporting process reached 94% in 60 days. I assumed ownership of being the main change agent. Example: a senior manager resisted the 'bureaucratic overhead' of the new risk template. I sat with him for 2 hours, we mapped together the risks of his R$ 3.2M project, and identified 2 critical risks (dependency on legacy system without backup + key person risk) that weren't on his radar. When he realized he could have lost R$ 800k due to these blind spots, he became the methodology's biggest advocate. I introduced the concept of OKRs to the public sector. I challenged managers not to report just status ('task X complete'), but the value the project was generating for Rio Grande do Sul citizens. My focus was changing the mindset from 'meeting schedule' to 'delivering sustainable impact that justifies public investment'.",
